Load the Data

We will use two separate data sets for this homework.

  1. The first data set represent sightings of grizzly bears (Ursos arctos) in Alaska.

  2. The second data set is from Brandell, Ellen E (2021), Serological dataset and R code for: Patterns and processes of pathogen exposure in gray wolves across North America, Dryad, Dataset.

  1. How many distinct wolf populations are included in this study? Mae a new object that restricts the data to the wolf populations in the lower 48 US states.
wolves %>%
  summarize(populations = n_distinct(pop))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   populations
##         <int>
## 1          17
wolves_usa <- wolves %>% 
  filter(lat >= 24.7433195 & lat <= 49.3457868 & long >= -124.7844079 & long <= -66.9513812)
  1. Use the albersusa package to make a base map of the lower 48 US states.
us_comp <- usa_sf()
lower_48 <- us_comp %>% 
  filter(name != "Hawaii" & name != "Alaska")
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = lower_48, size = 0.125) + 
  theme_linedraw()+
  labs(title = "USA State Boundaries")

  1. Use the relimited data to plot the distribution of wolf populations in the lower 48 US states.
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = lower_48, size = 0.125) + 
  geom_point(data = wolves_usa, aes(long, lat, color = pop), size = 2.5)+  
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Spectral")+
  labs(title = "Continental US Wolf Populations", x = NULL, y = NULL)

  1. What is the average pack size for the wolves in this study by region?
wolves %>% 
  group_by(pop) %>% 
  summarise(mean_pack = mean(pack_size))
